Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.030
[Music]

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:12.360
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to look at how letters arise in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:20.550
algebra in the context of identities. We've&nbsp;
had already our share of identities when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.550 --> 00:00:27.210
were talking about the foundations of arithmetic,&nbsp;
the basic laws satisfied by arithmetic with, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.210 --> 00:00:36.570
rational numbers. For example, we observe that&nbsp;
m plus n equals n plus m for any natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:46.830
m and n. So this one single expression captures&nbsp;
at once a whole range of possible formulas valid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:54.720
for particular numbers. Special cases of this&nbsp;
are, for example, 1 plus 2 equals 2 plus 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.720 --> 00:01:03.090
or 2 plus 5 equals 5 plus 2, or 13 plus 24&nbsp;
equals 24 plus 13, or trillions of other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:07.620
examples you could come up with. All of&nbsp;
these are special cases of this one law.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:15.120
We also framed some other laws: the commutative&nbsp;
law for multiplication, the distributive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:21.300
law, the associative law for addition, and the&nbsp;
associative law for multiplication. In each case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:29.790
the m's, k's, and n's represent arbitrary numbers&nbsp;
of a particular kind. So an algebraic identity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.790 --> 00:01:36.480
encodes a law which is valid for generally&nbsp;
any values assigned to the variables. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:42.120
is a rule that's valid no matter which&nbsp;
natural numbers we substitute for m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:47.520
k, and n. That's an important&nbsp;
usage of letters in algebra.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:54.690
Now there are many very rich identities in&nbsp;
mathematics, starting from relatively simple ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.690 --> 00:02:03.270
to progressively more complicated ones to very&nbsp;
rich and sophisticated identities. Let's start off&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:09.240
by looking at some fundamental identities that are&nbsp;
important for almost all students of mathematics.

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:17.370
Next to the basic laws of arithmetic that we've&nbsp;
already talked about, I think the simple quadratic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:26.430
identities are the next in line. We're talking&nbsp;
about what (a + b) squared is. So that's (a + b)&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:34.140
times (a + b), and all students learn that it's&nbsp;
a squared plus 2ab plus b squared. So this is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:39.450
identity that allows us to replace this with&nbsp;
this or conversely this with this whenever we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.450 --> 00:02:46.710
find it in an expression. A simple variant&nbsp;
is (a - b) squared. It's almost the same;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:54.510
it's a squared minus 2ab plus b squared. And of&nbsp;
course, we can verify these identities by simply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.510 --> 00:03:02.910
using the distributive law to expand (a - b) times&nbsp;
(a - b), for example. Another important quadratic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:11.040
identity is the difference of squares: (a + b)&nbsp;
times (a - b) equals a squared minus b squared.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:18.270
Next in line, I suppose in terms&nbsp;
of simplicity and importance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:26.130
are the geometric series identities. The first&nbsp;
one is really just a special case of this one:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:35.310
the fact that (1 + r) times (1 - r) equals 1 -&nbsp;
r squared. Now you might ask why am I switching&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.310 --> 00:03:42.990
from a's and b's to r? Well, that's because&nbsp;
in traditional mathematics, certain kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:50.010
identities have certain variables associated with&nbsp;
them, and so I'm trying to use the notation that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:56.760
most commonly associated with the identities&nbsp;
that we're talking about. A variant on this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.760 --> 00:04:05.340
slightly more complicated, is (1 + r + r squared)&nbsp;
times (1 - r). It's important to verify that when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:13.050
you multiply this all out and collect terms, you&nbsp;
get 1 - r cubed because here you have 1 + r + r&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.050 --> 00:04:21.390
squared and here you have -r - r squared&nbsp;
- r cubed. So the r squared terms cancel;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:29.470
you're just left with 1 - r cubed. That kind of&nbsp;
telescoping or collapsing of intermediate terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:36.670
happens from larger expressions. If we take (1 +&nbsp;
r + r squared + r cubed) and multiply by (1 - r),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.670 --> 00:04:44.860
again the only thing that's left after you expand&nbsp;
and cancel is 1 - r to the fourth. Then there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.860 --> 00:04:51.190
an obvious pattern that's established here, and&nbsp;
we can write the general law involving not just a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.190 --> 00:05:01.210
general letter r representing a number but also in&nbsp;
terms of a general exponent n, generalizing the 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:07.780
3, 4, and so on that appeared here. So in this&nbsp;
context, the n represents a natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:14.920
1 in this sequence, while the r is potentially&nbsp;
a rational number. This very important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:22.060
formula is the geometric series formula: 1 + r +&nbsp;
r squared all the way up to r to the n is 1 - r to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:28.840
the n + 1 divided by 1 - r. It's what we get when&nbsp;
we take an expression like this and divide by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:36.520
1 - r. That would be the case when n is 3, and&nbsp;
because we're dividing by 1 - r, it's important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:42.460
to remember that the formula is only valid if this&nbsp;
denominator is not 0, so we have to require that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:50.950
r is not equal to 1. The geometric series formula&nbsp;
is often written like this, slightly more general,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:58.090
where the first term is a instead of one, but each&nbsp;
term after that is obtained by multiplying by r.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.090 --> 00:06:08.740
So the sum a + ar all the way up to ar to the n&nbsp;
is a times 1 - r to the n + 1 divided by 1 - r.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:17.140
Here are two special identities that play a&nbsp;
particularly important role in geometry. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:24.130
first one we could call the Pythagorean identity,&nbsp;
and here's the simple form: (1 - h squared) all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:32.560
squared plus (2h) all squared equals (1 + h&nbsp;
squared) squared. I've decided to use h instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:41.710
of some other variable for a pretty good reason.&nbsp;
A generalization of this is m squared minus (n&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:50.920
squared all squared) plus (2mn) all squared equals&nbsp;
(m squared + n squared) all squared. All students&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:57.220
of mathematics should verify this formula by&nbsp;
explicitly expanding both sides and showing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.220 --> 00:07:05.440
that they are in fact the same. The connection&nbsp;
of this formula with Pythagorean triples is well&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:13.330
known. For any values of m and n, natural numbers,&nbsp;
we're getting three numbers here which have the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:19.390
property that this squared plus this squared&nbsp;
equals this squared, giving us the sides of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:27.760
right triangle according to Pythagoras' theorem.&nbsp;
So for example, if m is 2 and n is 1, then these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:35.680
three numbers inside the brackets become 3, 4,&nbsp;
and 5. 3 squared plus 4 squared equals 5 squared.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.790 --> 00:07:40.960
You can generate other Pythagorean triples&nbsp;
simply by changing the values of m and n.

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:49.090
Here are two other important identities that&nbsp;
are almost the same: Fibonacci's identities.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:57.790
This quantity squared plus this quantity squared&nbsp;
equals this times this, and a slight variant:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.790 --> 00:08:03.670
this same squared plus this thing squared&nbsp;
equals again the same product of things.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:11.260
These two identities are crucial for&nbsp;
trigonometry and for complex numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:17.920
These are also important identities that all&nbsp;
students of maths should verify by expansion.

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:27.340
Next time we're going to talk about probably&nbsp;
the most common and useful of all identities:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:33.250
the binomial theorem, which is&nbsp;
a centerpiece of high school&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:39.850
mathematics. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:08:40.930 --> 00:08:41.930
[Music]

